fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let X and Y be sets. For any set A and function f: A \to X and g: A \to Y, there exists a unique function h: A \to X \times Y such that the following diagram commutes:
\usepackage {tikz-cd} \usepackage {amssymb}
\begin {tikzcd} & {X \times Y} \\ X && Y \\ & A \arrow ["{ \pi _1}"', from=1-2, to=2-1] \arrow ["{ \pi _2}", from=1-2, to=2-3] \arrow ["f", from=3-2, to=2-1] \arrow ["g"', from=3-2, to=2-3] \arrow ["{ \exists !}", dashed, from=3-2, to=1-2] \end {tikzcd}
We might denote the unique function by \langle f,g \rangle : A \to X \times Y. It is sufficient to define \langle f,g \rangle (a) = (f(a),g(a)) for all a \in A as the unique function.

Let X and Y be sets. For any set A and function
f : X  \to  A and g : Y  \to  A, there exists a unique function
h : X  \sqcup  Y  \to  A such that the following diagram commutes:


   \usepackage {tikz-cd}
   \usepackage {amssymb}


     \begin {tikzcd}
        & A  \\ 
        X && Y  \\ 
        & {X \sqcup  Y}
         \arrow ["{i_1}"', from=2-1, to=3-2]
         \arrow ["{i_2}", from=2-3, to=3-2]
         \arrow ["f", from=2-1, to=1-2]
         \arrow ["g"', from=2-3, to=1-2]
         \arrow ["{ \exists !}", dashed, from=3-2, to=1-2]
     \end {tikzcd}   



We might denote the unique as f \sqcup  g: X  \sqcup  Y  \to  A.

Suppose we have sets X, Y, and Z and functions
f : X  \to  Z and g : Y  \to  Z.


   \usepackage {tikz-cd}
   \usepackage {amssymb}


     \begin {tikzcd}
        & Y  \\ 
        X & Z
         \arrow ["f"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
         \arrow ["g", from=1-2, to=2-2]
     \end {tikzcd}



Its fiber product is the set
         X  \times _Z Y =  \{   (x,w,y)  \mid  f(x) = w = g(y)   \}      
There are obvious projections 
          \pi _1 : X  \times _Z Y  \to  X  \text { and }  \pi _2 : X  \times _Z Y  \to  Y     
such that the following diagram commutes (W = X  \times _Z Y):


   \usepackage {tikz-cd}
   \usepackage {amssymb}


     \begin {tikzcd}
        W & Y  \\ 
        X & Z
         \arrow ["f"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
         \arrow ["g", from=1-2, to=2-2]
         \arrow ["{ \pi _2}", from=1-1, to=1-2]
         \arrow ["{ \pi _1}"', from=1-1, to=2-1]
         \arrow [" \lrcorner "{anchor=center, pos=0.125}, draw=none, from=1-1, to=2-2]
     \end {tikzcd}



The pullback is defined to be any set W  \cong  X \times _Z Y
The corner symbol indicates W is a pullback

